Recurrent Neural Networks


<!--

Pasquale Minervini

p.minervini@cs.ucl.ac.uk

-->

University College London

Statistical Natural Language Processing Course, UCL

9th December 2016

Language Models (LMs)¶

A language model computes a probability for a sequence of words

$$p(w_{1}, \ldots, w_{d})$$

Useful in a miriad of NLP tasks, such as machine translation:

$$p(\text{I}, \text{go}, \text{home}) > p(\text{I}, \text{go}, \text{house})$$

In $n$-gram language models, the probability $p(w_{1}, \ldots, w_{d})$ of observing the sentence $(w_{1}, \ldots, w_{d})$ is approximated as:

$$p(w_{1}, \ldots, w_{T}) = \prod_{i=1}^{m} p(w_{i} \mid w_{1}, \ldots, w_{i - 1}) \\ \approx \prod_{i=1}^{m} p(w_{i} \mid w_{i - (n - 1)}, \ldots, w_{i - 1})$$

Example with a bigram ($n = 2$) language model:

$$p(\text{I}, \text{go}, \text{home}) \approx p(\text{I} \mid \text{}) \; p(\text{go} \mid \text{I}) \; p(\text{home} \mid \text{go})$$

A Simple Recurrent Neural Network (RNN) LM¶

Given a list of word vectors (e.g. one-hot, word2vec, GloVe):

$$x_{1}, \ldots, x_{t - 1}, x_{t}, x_{t + 1}, \ldots, x_{d}$$

At a single time step:

$$ \begin{aligned} \mathbf{h}_t & = \text{sigmoid}(\mathbf{W}^h \mathbf{h}_{t-1}+ \mathbf{W}^x \mathbf{x}_t + \mathbf{b}) \\ \mathbf{y}_{t} & = \text{softmax}(\mathbf{W}^o \mathbf{h}_{t}) \\ \end{aligned} $$

where $\mathbf{y}_{t} \in \mathbb{R}^{|V|}$ is a probability distribution over words in the vocabulary $V$.

The probability that the $t$-th word is $w_{j}$ is given by:

$$p(w_{j} \mid x_{t}, \ldots, x_{1}) = \mathbf{y}_{t, j}$$

Example¶

Consider the word sequence $(\text{I}, \text{go}, \text{home}) \rightarrow (x_{1}, x_{2}, x_{3}, x_{4})$

Reminder: $\mathbf{h}_t = \text{sigmoid}(\mathbf{W}^h \mathbf{h}_{t-1}+ \mathbf{W}^x \mathbf{x}_t + \mathbf{b})$

$$ \begin{aligned} \mathbf{h}_1 = \text{sigmoid}(\mathbf{W}^h \mathbf{h}_{0} + \mathbf{W}^x \mathbf{x}_1) &\;& \hat{\mathbf{y}}_{1} = \text{softmax}(\mathbf{W}^o \mathbf{h}_{1}) \\ \mathbf{h}_2 = \text{sigmoid}(\mathbf{W}^h \mathbf{h}_{1} + \mathbf{W}^x \mathbf{x}_2) &\;& \hat{\mathbf{y}}_{2} = \text{softmax}(\mathbf{W}^o \mathbf{h}_{2}) \\ \mathbf{h}_3 = \text{sigmoid}(\mathbf{W}^h \mathbf{h}_{2} + \mathbf{W}^x \mathbf{x}_3) &\;& \hat{\mathbf{y}}_{3} = \text{softmax}(\mathbf{W}^o \mathbf{h}_{3}) \\ \end{aligned} $$$$p(\text{I}, \text{go}, \text{home}) = \hat{\mathbf{y}}_{1, [\text{I}]} \; \hat{\mathbf{y}}_{2, [\text{go}]} \; \hat{\mathbf{y}}_{3, [\text{home}]}$$
  • $\mathbf{h}_{0} \in \mathbb{R}^{D_{h}}$ is an initialization vector
  • $\mathbf{W}^h \in \mathbb{R}^{D_{h} \times D_{h}}$, $\mathbf{W}^x \in \mathbb{R}^{D_{h} \times D_{x}}$, $\mathbf{W}^o \in \mathbb{R}^{|V| \times D_{h}}$ are model parameters

Such parameters can be learned from data.

Objective Function for LMs¶

Recall that $\mathbf{y}_{t} \in \mathbb{R}^{|V|}$ is a probability distribution over the vocabulary $V$.

We can train a RNN by minimizing the cross-entropy loss, predicting words instead of classes:

$$ \begin{aligned} J^{t} = - \sum_{i = 1}^{|V|} \mathbf{y}_{t, i} \log \hat{\mathbf{y}}_{t, i}, \quad \mathbf{y}_{t, i} = \left\{\begin{array}{ll}1 \; \text{if the $t$-th word is $w_{i}$,}\\0 \, \text{otherwise.}\end{array} \right. \end{aligned} $$

Evaluation - negative of average log-probability over corpus:

$$J = - \frac{1}{T} \sum_{t = 1}^{T} \sum_{j = 1}^{|V|} \mathbf{y}_{t, j} \log \hat{\mathbf{y}}_{t, j}$$

Or also PERPLEXITY:

$$PP(w_1,\ldots,w_T) = \sqrt[T]{\prod_{i = 1}^T \frac{1}{p(w_i | w_{1}, \ldots, w_{i-1})}}$$

Sequence-to-Sequence Models¶

A RNN can also generate sequences - Seq2Seq models are composed by:

  • An encoded that processes the input and generates a vector $\mathbf{v} \in \mathbb{R}^{d}$
  • A decoder that generates the output starting from $\mathbf{v}$

Widely popular in e.g. Neural Machine Translation and Learning to Execute

Problem - Training RNNs is Hard¶

  • Vanashing and Exploding gradients

Why? - Multiply the same matrix at each time step during forward propagation. The gradient might either tend to 0 (vanish) or be too large (explode).

Several solution in the literature:

  • Bound the gradient to a threshold (Gradient Clipping) [<span class=blue>Pascanu et al. 2013</span>]
  • Use $\text{ReLU}(x) = \max(0, x)$ as a non-linearity instead of $\text{sigmoid}(x)$ [<span class=blue>Glorot et al. 2011</span>].
  • Clever initialization of parameters ($\mathbf{W}^h = \mathbf{I}$) [<span class=blue>Socher et al. 2013</span>, <span class=blue>Le et al. 2015</span>].
  • Use different recurrent network architectures that favour backpropagation (such as Long Short-Term Memory networks [<span class=blue>Hochreiter et al. 1997</span>]).

\begin{align} \mathbf{H}_t &= \left[ \begin{array}{*{20}c} \mathbf{x}_t \\ \mathbf{h}_{t-1} \end{array} \right]\\ \mathbf{i}_t &= \sigma(\mathbf{W}^i\mathbf{H}+\mathbf{b}^i)\\ \mathbf{f}_t &= \sigma(\mathbf{W}^f\mathbf{H}+\mathbf{b}^f)\\ \mathbf{o}_t &= \sigma(\mathbf{W}^o\mathbf{H}+\mathbf{b}^o)\\ \mathbf{c}_t &= \mathbf{f}_t \odot \mathbf{c}_{t-1} + \mathbf{i}_t \odot \tanh(\mathbf{W}^c\mathbf{H}+\mathbf{b}^c)\\ \mathbf{h}_t &= \mathbf{o}_t \odot \tanh(\mathbf{c}_t) \end{align}
